## pie> ## Another case showing pie() is rather fun than science:
## pie> ## (original by FinalBackwardsGlance on http://imgur.com/gallery/wWrpU4X)
## pie> pie(c(Sky = 78, "Sunny side of pyramid" = 17, "Shady side of pyramid" = 5),
## pie+     init.angle = 315, col = c("deepskyblue", "yellow", "yellow3"), border = FALSE)

pie(c(10, 20, 30))

q <- c(10, 20, 30)
l <- c("Crianças", "Mulheres", "Homens")
pie(q, l)

q <- c(10, 20, 30)
l <- c("Crianças", "Mulheres", "Homens")

pie(q, l, init.angle = 90)

q <- c(10, 20, 30)
l <- c("Crianças", "Mulheres", "Homens")

pie(q, l, init.angle = 90, main="Pessoas")

q <- c(10, 20, 30)
l <- c("Crianças", "Mulheres", "Homens")

color <- c("blue", "yellow", "green")

pie(q, l, init.angle = 90, main="Pessoas", col = color)

q <- c(10, 20, 30)
l <- c("Crianças", "Mulheres", "Homens")

color <- c("blue", "yellow", "green")

pie(q, l, init.angle = 90, main="Pessoas", col = color)
legend("bottomright", l, fill = color)
